itish observers made concerning the colony’s return to Chinese sovereignty. An epilogue considers the enduring legacy of British colonialism.This book will be essential reading for historians of Hong Kong, British decolonisation, and Britain’s culture of declinism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aBritish culture.  aBritishness.  aDecolonization.  aHong Kong.  aImperial governance.  aModernization.1 aHampton, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499692540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784996925423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784996925/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles